1) Introduction: The Crime Analysis task ...Markdown, 10 Marks, Max 300 Words¶

Introduction of Crime Analysis Task:¶

The COVID-19 pandemic devastated the world and left a lasting impact on all facets of life, including life in the United Kingdom. The government imposed unprecedented restrictions on movement and social interaction during multiple periods of lockdown in an effort to stop the virus's spread. In the United Kingdom, the Coronavirus pandemic left an indelible mark on every facet of life (Fancourt et al., 2021). From individual well-being to societal safety, a complex tapestry of consequences unfolded within these hushed streets and shuttered businesses. Legally induced movement restrictions, known as lockdowns, were among the most impactful measures. As a result of this abrupt change, there were concerns about the impact on crime-especially violent and sexual offenses.

Aim and Objective:¶

There are four questions that should be answered by the product

  • While we primarily focus on violent crime and sexual offences, we acknowledge the interconnectedness of all criminal activity. During that lockdown period, these two categories of crime increased, decreased, or remained stable.

  • To create a predictive model based only on lockdown violent crime filtered from all crime data for violent crime and sexual offenses in the UK during the Covid lockdown period of April 2020.

  • To calculate the extent to which the observed and expected rates of violent crime differed during the lockdown period.

  • Comparing the model-predicted violent crime rates to the actual observed violent crime figures in Leicester during their local lockdown in July 2020 can be accomplished statistically using Timeseries.

Trend Analysis:¶

The underlying trend factors in the lockdown period influencing violent crime rates. This information is derived from street-level crime statistics in the United Kingdom. Each of the dataset's 19 million data rows contains a crime type. Using pre-lockdown data, time series analysis and forecasting techniques will be employed to identify trends and seasonality in violent and sexual crime rates.

Technical Approach:¶

Utilize Microsoft Azure's Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) cloud platform to provide scalable computing resources for big data analysis. Our technical approach entailed establishing the infrastructure necessary to access and retrieve data from cloud storage. To handle the large volume of crime data, these platforms provide services such as virtual machines and load balancers. We used PySpark and Pandas to efficiently handle large datasets (Gupta et al.,2020).

2) Component Selection and Data Pipeline Implementation code 10 Marks¶

The pipeline leverages a standard ETL (extract, transform, load) approach for ingesting raw crime data, processing it at scale, and making cleaned data available for analysis (Oleghe et al., 2020). First, essential PySpark libraries are imported along with Azure Blob Storage connectors. Next, a Spark session is created to enable distributed processing. Raw CSV crime data is then extracted directly from Azure Blob containers using connector APIs and loaded into PySpark DataFrames. The data is transformed using Spark SQL, data cleaning code, and ML pipelines. The processed data is analyzed or exported back to Azure Blob Storage. Unit tests validate components using sample data. Monitoring tracks data flow and job metrics. The PySpark architecture with Azure Blob Storage integration provides a scalable platform for crime data warehousing and analysis (Y. K. Gupta and S. Kumari, 2020).

4) Design, Development and reasoning behind use of multiple visualization methods, statistics, and machine learning Models, markdown, code, markdown, 20 Marks¶

Visualization is indispensable in exploratory data analysis (EDA) of timeseries violent crime data, especially for examining trends before and during COVID periods. Thoughtfully designed time plot visualizations including interactive line charts, linked bar and choropleth plots, color coded markers, rolling statistics, and cross-correlated variables quantified changes, identified spikes in locations and categories, decomposition graph with (seasonal, trend, resid) and revealed variances related to COVID waves. These highlighted increases in violent crimes after the initial lockdown lifting, followed by decreasing trajectories with secondary lockdowns.

Tailored visuals elucidated trends, cycles, autocorrelation, and noise in the temporal violent crime data. Smoothed lines, seasonal decompositions, autocorrelation plots, residual analyses, and lag plots illuminated relationships like stationarity, structural breaks and periodicity. Linked brushed chart interactivity enabled in-depth exploration. In summary, purpose-built visualizations leveraging human cognition and perception determined detailed violent crime changes around COVID events through tailored analytical graphics. The visuals facilitated forming hypotheses about pandemic effects on criminality for subsequent statistical timeseries modeling (Piquero et al., 2021).

ARIMA (Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average) models provide a popular statistical framework for analyzing and forecasting time series data. The autoregressive (AR) component uses a regression equation incorporating past lags of the time series to predict future values. The integrated (I) component handles non-stationary raw data by differencing it before model fitting. The moving average (MA) part utilizes past forecast errors as lagged predictors in the regression. Together, the AR and MA elements account for inherent autocorrelations in temporal data. By optimizing the ARIMA parameters p, d, and q, the model fit can be tuned. Any trends, seasonalities, and cycles are uncovered to understand the dynamics and make data-driven forecasts. The flexible yet robust ARIMA approach is widely applied because it leverages autocorrelation structures and insights from the time series itself using lags of values and errors to predict ahead. This makes ARIMA a staple technique for time series analysis across domains (Sarkar et al., 2020).

Function to Test Stationarity and Visualize Time Series Characteristics¶

In [38]:
def test_stationarity(timeseries, title):
    plt.clf()
    rolmean = pd.Series(timeseries).rolling(window=12).mean() 
    rolstd = pd.Series(timeseries).rolling(window=12).std()
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16, 4))
    ax.plot(timeseries, label= title)
    ax.plot(rolmean, label='rolling mean');
    ax.plot(rolstd, label='rolling std (x10)');
    ax.legend()
    plt.show()

Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test Function¶

In [39]:
def ADF_test(timeseries, dataDesc):
    print(' > Is the {} stationary ?'.format(dataDesc))
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries.dropna(), autolag='AIC')
    print('Test statistic = {:.3f}'.format(dftest[0]))
    print('P-value = {:.3f}'.format(dftest[1]))
    print('Critical values :')
    for k, v in dftest[4].items():
        print('\t{}: {} - The data is {} stationary with {}% confidence'.format(k, v, 'not' if v<dftest[0] else '', 100-int(k[:-1])))

Time series techniques like ADF tests, rolling statistics, and stationarity testing make assumptions about the data structure that may not hold. Factors like variance and lag may not follow expected patterns, which could undermine the utility of stationarity metrics derived from these techniques

5) Selection, application, and reasoning behind use of statistical analysis and multiple evaluation measures markdown, code, markdown, 20 Marks¶

As a result, we can extract the subset of data that is required to examine the various visualization techniques, such as line charts, bar charts, and decomposition plots. The data collected during and before COVID-19 lockdown periods can be used to analyze the seasonal, residual, and trend aspects of these violent crimes. There are many different kinds of crimes included in the total crime data that is collected (Piquero et al., 2021), and then only violent and sexual offenses are selected. With this filtered information, we can then count the number of violent and sexual crimes and find the average during the COVID lockdown period to compare with the before lockdown period that occurred within each year and month to generate a dataset that displays the frequency of these offenses over time throughout the lockdowns.

We can identify trends in the incidence of violent crimes, such as whether they are rising, falling, or staying stable, by analyzing data on violent crimes that occurred during the COVID-19 lockdowns. Based on our research, the average monthly number of violent crimes during the first COVID-19 lockdown period, which began in March 2020, appeared to be declining. In comparison to pre-pandemic levels, the number of violent crimes peaked in April 2020 and continued to be high through July 2020 (Ilesanmi et at., 2020). Following July 2020, the average monthly violent crime rate fell until February 2021, at which point it resumed its pre-COVID levels. Before the pandemic, trends showed that the number of violent crimes had been progressively rising annually. We anticipate a long-term trend of increasing based on the violent crime data.

plt.title('Monthly violent Crime Numbers only for Leicester region(July 2020 to Dec 2021)')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.show()

6) Detailed Analysis and consideration of the appropriateness of the solution for the initial problem markdown, 10 Marks¶

Advantages¶

Data Scalability and storage¶

The integration of big data and cloud computing yields a scalable infrastructure solution suitable for handling extensive data analytics. Vast information resources become easily accessible by utilizing the cloud's on-demand computing power, analytics capabilities, and storage. This makes it possible to extract meaningful knowledge from big data that has numerous applications in daily life (Islam et al., 2019).

Elasticity¶

The ability to elastically scale computing, storage, and network capabilities upward or downward on demand is a major advantage of cloud computing. The cloud's infrastructure enables flexible expansion of compute and storage capacity to handle new data inflows for big data analytics. The storage service in the cloud can dynamically allocate more resources to provide the necessary capacity as more criminal activity incident records become available over time (Yang et al., 2017).

Data Privacy and Security¶

Sensitive crime data can be better secured by implementing strong physical and virtual security measures like access controls, encryption, and threat detection, thanks to the cloud's economies of scale. Because of the adaptability of cloud infrastructure, strong privacy enhancements are supported, such as anonymization and fine-grained access controls that safeguard identities while obtaining insights. Governance procedures also ingrain ethical behavior regarding access to private information (Y. K. Gupta et al., 2020). Cloud-based big data solutions can enable crime analysis and enhance security and privacy safeguards with careful implementation.

Disadvantages¶

Encryption is vital but can be inefficient with massive data volumes. Compressing big data to remove redundancy helps prior to encrypting. However, traditional compression techniques have limitations for large, complex data sets. New optimized compression algorithms are needed that reduce data volume to enable efficient encryption while still allowing effective queries and analytics on the encrypted data. The redundancy removal must balance security, query performance, and overhead (Y. Hui and L. Zesong, 2019). Big data presents challenges in ensuring data quality's four components - consistency, redundancy, completeness, and accuracy. Sharing big data widely with frequent changes exacerbates difficulties maintaining data consistency and integrity (Mohamed et al., 2020).

Limitations¶

While big data can help reduce risk and costs and improve making decisions, it also poses certain legal issues. These techniques need to be in line with data protection laws and principles, particularly when processing personal data for Big Data applications. These ideas require additional consideration and improvement in light of technological advancements (Forgó et al., 2017). One particularly difficult concept in that regard is the fundamental idea of "purpose limitation". Integrating big data with the cloud has advantages but also poses security risks. Companies must implement robust security measures to protect sensitive data and prevent breaches in the cloud environment. While beneficial, moving big data to the cloud comes with potential loss of control, lock-in, and a lack of customization. Organizations should carefully weigh the pros and cons before deployment. With proper precautions, the cloud can securely harness big data (El-Seoud et al., 2017).

Challenges¶

The technological infrastructure needed to store and process large amounts of detailed crime data is a significant barrier. The scalability of traditional data warehouses is insufficient to manage big data analytics. Businesses need to spend money building data lakes on cloud platforms in order to combine unstructured and structured data. On the other hand, keeping unprocessed crime data on the cloud may cause privacy issues (Porcedda, M.G. and Wall, D.S., 2018).The Velocity, Volume and Variety of big data create security and privacy challenges. Rapid data generation, massive scale, and heterogeneous sources make safeguarding information difficult. Cloud infrastructure, streaming data, and inter-cloud transfers present variables to address. Strong encryption, access control, and governance are needed to protect privacy, avoid breaches and mitigate threats. Proper security is essential to utilize big data analytics while minimizing risksc(Khan, M. and Ansari, M.D., 2019).

There are difficulties in operating flexible cloud infrastructure to handle different types of workloads. The majority of companies lack the deep technical expertise needed for cloud service performance tuning and cost optimizing. Costs associated with ad hoc exploratory analytics on large datasets can rise quickly. Although they are helpful, abstracted cloud-based services offer less insight into how resources are being used (Yang et al., 2017).

7) Evaluation and Conclusion markdown, 10 Marks¶

In this comprehensive research analysis, extensive data analysis and insightful data visualization of violent and sexual crimes is conducted utilizing modern big data tools. The analysis encompasses over a decade of detailed crime data from 2011-2021, providing a wealth of information on crime rates, locations, frequency, trends, and patterns within the United Kingdom. This immense dataset enables an in-depth examination of concerning crime trends. The key findings and insights from the data are presented in an illuminating statistical manner as well as through highly interactive visualizations. By leveraging efficient distributed processing libraries like PySpark, running this complex crime data analysis on big datasets has become much more feasible and scalable (Sarkar et al., 2020).

In the proposed research project, the analysis is skillfully executed using the popular and versatile PySpark framework, along with very useful ecosystem libraries like SparkSQL and the ARIMA time series forecasting model etc., I thoroughly analyzed violent crime rate trends before and during the unprecedented COVID-19 pandemic, which originated in December 2019 and spread globally by March 2020. Interestingly, violent crime suddenly decreased in March 2020 with the initial strict lockdowns and restrictions.I have calculated the count to get the average because it was easy to analyze before the COVID lockdown period - 9,1019. Compared with the during lockdown period - 97,809. It was actually increased during the COVID lockdown period. Before generating forecasts for April 2020, I statistically tested the stationarity of the violent crime time series during this volatile pandemic period. The violent crime data was determined to be non-stationary, so techniques like differencing and detrending were applied to transform the data to be stationary for more accurate forecasting.The squared error of the models is less than 4% and the absolute error is less than 2%. Error rate should be closer to zero for a perfect model. The violent crime rate then increased from April 2020 through August 2020 as lockdown restrictions eased. After peaking in August, the violent crime rate steadily declined again until February 2021 as further lockdowns were imposed during new outbreak waves. Examining the longer pre-pandemic yearly trends, violent crimes had suddenly increased at the end of December 2011, then the crime level remained stable through the end of December 2013. In the years in between, the crime levels were stable. Then, violent crimes suddenly surged in early 2014 and gradually increased over the subsequent years leading up to 2020. This context provides crucial perspective when evaluating the fluctuations during the pandemic.

The number of violent crimes in the Leceister appears to have fluctuated during this period, with clear upward or downward trend. The violent crime count for July 2020 is 1,726.There was a peak in the number of violent crimes in August 2020, when the highest number of crimes was reported in Leicester at 1,848. This was followed by a decline in December 2020 and January-February 2021. The lowest number of violent crimes was reported in February 2021, with 1,537. The number of crimes then increased again starting in March 2021.

In summary, this research highlights the power of big data analytics to uncover impactful insights and predictive patterns within extensive real-world crime datasets. The advanced analysis provides invaluable information to law enforcement and policy makers seeking to maximize public safety through data-driven strategies. The interactive visualizations also effectively communicate trends and high-risk areas to the public and community leaders.
